04928nam a22007095i 9780748629077DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222007stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486290777 a10.1515/97807486290772doi  a(DE-B1597)614826  a(OCoLC)1306541264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aJC261.L32aJC261.L32S73 2007 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.0191 aStavrakakis, Yannis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Lacanian Left :bPsychoanalysis, Theory, Politics /cYannis Stavrakakis. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tBibliographical Note -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Locating the Lacanian Left -- tPart I Theory: Dialectics of Disavowal -- t1 Antinomies of Creativity: Lacan and Castoriadis on Social Construction and the Political -- t2 Laclau with Lacan on Jouissance: Negotiating the Affective Limits of Discourse -- t3 Žižekian ‘Perversions’: The Lure of Antigone and the Fetishism of the Act -- tPart II Analysis: Dialectics of Enjoyment -- t4 What Sticks? From Symbolic Power to Jouissance -- t5 Enjoying the Nation: A Success Story? -- t6 Lack of Passion: European Identity Revisited -- t7 The Consumerist ‘Politics of Jouissance’ and the Fantasy of Advertising -- t8 Democracy in Post-Democratic Times -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years psychoanalysis - especially Lacanian theory - has been gradually acknowledged as a vital resource in the ongoing re-orientation of contemporary political theory and analysis. Of particular note is that the work of Jacques Lacan is increasingly being used by major political philosophers associated with the Left. This indicates the dynamic emergence of a new theoretico-political horizon: that of the 'Lacanian Left'. However, this has yet to be properly conceived and structured as a field. The Lacanian Left is the first book to bring it into academic consciousness and to draw its implications for concrete political analysis in a systematic way. It offers:An accessible mapping of its main contours.A detailed examination of the points of convergence and divergence between the major figures active or at the periphery of this terrain, including Slavoj Zizek, Ernesto Laclau, Alain Badiou and Cornelius Castoriadis.A critical evaluation of their respective arguments on social construction and the political, affectivity and discourse, ethics and social change, negativity and positivity. Engaging with the role of affect and emotion in political life through the central Lacanian notion of 'enjoyment', The Lacanian Left puts forward innovative analyses of political power and authority, nationalism, European identity, consumerism and advertising culture, de-democratisation and post-democracy. It will be of value to everyone interested in exploring the potential of psychoanalysis to reinvigorate political theory, critical political analysis and democratic politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPolitical psychology. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPsychoanalysisxPolitical aspects. 0aRight and left (Political science). 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074861980140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748629077?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748629077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748629077/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c